+The Android Debug Bridge (ADB) is a command-line tool that enables communication between a computer and an Android device. 
+It's part of the Android SDK (Software Development Kit) and is particularly useful for developers and device enthusiasts for various tasks such as debugging, installing apps, transferring files, and more.

+With appropriate permissions, ADB can be used to track Android devices by accessing device information, including location data. 
+It also allows users to access device logs, which can provide insights into the device's behavior and any errors or issues it encounters. 
+Additionally, ADB facilitates various debugging tasks, such as analyzing app performance, troubleshooting connectivity issues, and diagnosing software problems.



adb devices: Lists all connected Android devices or emulators.
adb shell: Opens a shell on the device to execute commands directly.
adb install <path_to_apk>: Installs an APK file onto the connected device.
adb uninstall <package_name>: Uninstalls an app from the connected device.
adb logcat: Displays the device log in real-time, showing system and app messages.
adb pull <remote> <local>: Copies a file or directory from the device to the computer.
adb push <local> <remote>: Copies a file or directory from the computer to the device.
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW -d <URL>: Opens a URL in the default browser on the device.
adb shell input keyevent <keycode>: Simulates a key press event on the device.
adb reboot: Reboots the connected device.

***************************************************************************************************************
To track the location of a mobile phone using ADB, you can use the following command:

-->$adb shell dumpsys location<--
